            },
            "answer_text": "For acoustics look to make sure that the bridge is not lifting or any neck joint body separation. Make sure there are no splits or cracks in the body. Make sure there are no sharp fret ends or loose machine heads and look for a solid top. Play the instrument and make sure it is comfortable in your hands and has a tone you are looking for. Make sure there are no dead frets or rattling from loose braces. For electrics look for a guitar that feels solid and has a good acoustic resonance, even though it\u2019s meant to be plugged in a dead piece of wood won\u2019t sound as good as a lively one. Make sure all the knobs and switches are tight and functional and that the pickups have a good sound without too much noise. Play the instrument and make sure that it feels good in your hands and has no dead frets of sharp fret edges. Both acoustic and electric make sure have good action and intonation the whole way up the neck. ",
